</comment>
                            <comment id="14558642" author="skuksenko" created="Wed, 8 Feb 2023 12:32:29 -0800"  >There is a risk (small risk) of potential performance regressions (small regressions) caused by enabling continuation by default.&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;br/&gt;
It may be caused by CPU microarchitecture. In some cases, post call nop instructions were generated inside hot loops, which causes a performance drop on CPU front-end level (Loop Stream Detector fail plus larger and less effective uop-cache work). That was proved by CPU HWC analysis. That happened/checked on both platforms - x86 and aarch64. First of all, it was observed only on several JMH microbenchmarks (no one large benchmark was affected). Performance regression is relatively small ~5%-7%. And the latter - my experience shows me that it&amp;#39;s unrealistic to tune code codegeneration to fulfill CPU LSD requirements. It&amp;#39;s too fragile area. &lt;br/&gt;
Conclusion: It&amp;#39;s ok to have such small regressions on some microbenchmarks.&lt;br/&gt;
</comment>
